  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's a lived reality for many of us who've struggled with the pressure of being perceived as less capable. As a barista in Philadelphia with a background that's shaped by my parents' academic achievements—my dad holding a PhD and my mom a master's degree—I've seen how deeply these stereotypes can affect people. Growing up in a household where education was valued, I expected to excel, but the reality of stereotype threat hit me hard when I started working in a tech support role. I remember a conversation with a colleague where she said, 'You're so smart, but you don't seem like you'd be good at coding.' That moment made me realize how quickly assumptions can derail potential. Given my own depression and the high neuroticism I struggle with, I know how much anxiety stereotypes can add. Should we address it? Absolutely. But the way we do it matters. We need to create environments where people feel safe to make mistakes without fear of judgment. In my daily life, I see this play out in how people interact online—social media can amplify stereotypes, but it can also be a space for connection and support. For example, when I play board games with my kids, I try to emphasize that everyone has unique strengths. This approach helps build a culture where people don't feel the pressure to conform to narrow expectations. Addressing stereotype threat in STEM requires more than just awareness—it needs systemic change, like mentorship programs that pair students with role models who share similar backgrounds. It's not just about fixing the problem; it's about fostering a community where everyone feels they belong.",
